1. Chosen Development Model
Model: Agile (Scrum)
Justification: A Lost and Found system requires frequent feedback on the UI/UX to ensure users can easily report items.
Agile allows for iterative development, enabling us to test the matching algorithm and notification system in sprints.

2. User Requirements
a. Stakeholders (WHO is involved)
* End-Users (Losers & Finders):
    Role: The primary users who create posts, search for items, and communicate to arrange returns.
    Interest: Finding their lost property quickly or ensuring a found item reaches its rightful owner safely.
* System Administrators:
    Role: Responsible for overseeing the platform, managing user disputes, and moderating content.
    Interest: Maintaining a clean, spam-free environment and ensuring the system runs smoothly.
* University/Organization Security (Optional Stakeholder):
    Role: Often act as the physical "holding point" for items.
    Interest: Having a digital log of what is currently in the physical lost and found office to reduce manual paperwork.
* Developers:
    Role: Technical team responsible for building, updating, and fixing bugs in the application.
    Interest: Building a scalable, bug-free system with high performance.
* Database Managers:
    Role: Specifically focused on data integrity and security.
    Interest: Ensuring that user data and uploaded images are stored securely and efficientl

b. User Stories (WHAT they need and WHY)
1.	As a Loser, I want to post a detailed description of my lost item so that others can identify it.
2.	As a Finder, I want to upload a photo of an item I found so that the owner can recognize it visually.
3.	As a Loser, I want to filter items by category (electronics, keys, etc.) so that I can find my item faster.
4.	As a Finder, I want to set a "Safe Meeting Point" so that I can return the item securely.
5.	As a User, I want to receive a push notification when a potential match is found so that I don't have to check the app constantly.
6.	As a User, I want to message a finder/loser within the app so that I don't have to share my private phone number.
7.	As an Admin, I want to flag and remove suspicious or "prank" posts so that the platform remains trustworthy.
8.	As a Loser, I want to mark an item as "Recovered" so that it no longer appears in the active search list.
9.	As a User, I want to search by "Last Seen Location" on a map so that I can see items found in specific areas.
10.	As a Guest, I want to browse found items without an account so that I can see if my item is there before signing up.


3.Functional Requirements (FR)
1.	Registration: System shall allow users to register via email/password.
2.	Login: System shall authenticate users.
3.	Create Post: Users shall be able to create "Lost" or "Found" posts.
4.	Image Upload: System shall support JPG/PNG uploads for items.
5.	Category Selection: System shall provide a dropdown of at least 10 item categories.
6.	Search Bar: System shall allow keyword searching in titles and descriptions.
7.	Location Tagging: System shall integrate a Map API for pinning locations.
8.	Status Update: System shall allow users to change post status to "Resolved."
9.	In-App Chat: System shall provide a real-time text interface between two users.
10.	Matching Algorithm: System shall automatically notify users if a "Lost" post matches a "Found" post's keywords.
11.	User Profile: Users shall be able to edit their contact details and profile picture.
12.	Admin Dashboard: Admins shall have a view of all active posts.
13.	Delete Post: Users shall be able to delete their own posts.
14.	Password Reset: System shall send a reset link via email.
15.	Report Post: Users shall be able to report a post for "Inappropriate Content."
16.	Filter by Date: Users shall be able to filter results by the date the item was lost/found.
17.	Notification Settings: Users shall be able to toggle email vs. push notifications.
18.	Multi-language Support: System shall support English and one local language.
19.	Activity Log: Users shall see a history of their own posts and interactions.
20.	Terms of Service: Users must agree to terms before posting.

b.Acceptance Criteria (When we know it WORKS correctly)


4. Non-Functional Requirements (NFR)
1.	Availability: System shall be available 99.9% of the time.
2.	Response Time: Pages must load in under 2 seconds.
3.	Concurrency: System must support 500 concurrent users.
4.	Mobile-First: The UI must be fully responsive for mobile devices.
5.	Data Encryption: All user passwords must be hashed using bcrypt.
6.	SSL: All data transmission must be over HTTPS.
7.	Database Backup: Daily backups of the database must be performed.
8.	Scalability: System should be deployable via Docker for easy scaling.
9.	Usability: A new user should be able to post an item in under 3 minutes.
10.	Privacy: User phone numbers must remain hidden unless the user chooses to share them.
11.	Maintainability: Code must follow PEP8 (if Python) or Airbnb Style Guide (if JS).
12.	Recoverability: System must recover from a crash within 15 minutes.
13.	Accessibility: The site must meet WCAG 2.1 Level AA standards (for color contrast).
14.	Audit Trail: All admin actions must be logged.
15.	Browser Compatibility: Must support Chrome, Firefox, and Safari.
16.	Search Efficiency: Database queries for searches must be indexed.
17.	File Size Limit: Images must be compressed to under 2MB before storage.
18.	Session Timeout: Idle users should be logged out after 30 minutes.
19.	Test Coverage: Backend code must have at least 80% unit test coverage.
20.	Localization: Date formats must adapt to the user's region (DD/MM/YYYY).

